121
00:15:08,014 --> 00:15:11,418
And there's a nice little video that I saw over there.

122
00:15:13,187 --> 00:15:17,071
And she talks about the great turning.

123
00:15:17,211 --> 00:15:31,124
She has this understanding, and other people do, that we are at a point where we could have a really great turnaround in the world to a completely different way of living, or at least a much more wholesome way of living.

124
00:15:32,164 --> 00:15:41,472
If we go back to the Buddha's time, that was a time which is called the Axial Age, where we had suddenly a raising of human consciousness.

125
00:15:41,756 --> 00:15:49,191
The Buddha, of course, there were the Brahminical sages who were writing the Upanishads.

126
00:15:49,572 --> 00:15:56,424
There was Lao Tzu in China, Moses in the desert, and of course, our own Socrates.

127
00:15:57,011 --> 00:16:06,403
And the message from all of these people was, do unto others as you would have them do unto you.

128
00:16:06,924 --> 00:16:10,489
That's one of the basic messages that came from that axial age.

129
00:16:10,509 --> 00:16:13,133
There were others too, but that was the basic one.

130
00:16:14,975 --> 00:16:16,937
Or one of the basic ones.

131
00:16:16,957 --> 00:16:22,664
And she talks about this moment of turning and what's necessary for it to happen.

132
00:16:23,793 --> 00:16:26,095
And she talks about three different things.

133
00:16:26,174 --> 00:16:33,001
First of all, holding actions to stop the destructiveness of what's happening.

134
00:16:33,062 --> 00:16:37,085
So we have, for instance, in this country, 2,000 food banks.

135
00:16:38,225 --> 00:16:41,909
I mean, that's the situation where people have to go to food banks to get food.

136
00:16:43,211 --> 00:16:52,720
We have the big issue, which is a newspaper that homeless people can sell on the streets in order to make a bit of money to pay for rent and stuff.

137
00:16:53,846 --> 00:17:08,265
Recently we've had the ecologist Chris Packman stopping the extension to Heathrow Airport by going to the courts and saying it would undermine the aim we have of reducing our carbon footprint.

138
00:17:09,086 --> 00:17:23,584
And he's now in the process of trying to stop that HS2, the fast speed railway that's going to rip up half of England in order to get to the north quicker.

139
00:17:24,948 --> 00:17:39,910
And so all these are really trying to undermine the destructiveness of this particular form of economics we have, neoliberal economics.

140
00:17:40,631 --> 00:17:47,721
So that's the first thing, that there are people who are trying to limit the damage.

141
00:17:47,740 --> 00:17:53,789
Then she goes on to say that the next thing is that we need alternative structures and patterns of organizing.

142
00:17:55,019 --> 00:18:04,515
And one of the things she talks about is organic farming, turning away from prosperity towards human happiness, what makes us happy.

143
00:18:05,636 --> 00:18:10,825
And, you know, the use of plastic, looking at that very closely.

144
00:18:10,865 --> 00:18:14,832
So there's all that business of actually doing something differently.

145
00:18:16,555 --> 00:18:19,660
And I think in many ways that's beginning to happen perhaps.

146
00:18:20,280 --> 00:18:30,730
But the third one and really the foundation of any turning point that has to come is, of course, a change of values, depending on our belief systems.

147
00:18:32,932 --> 00:18:43,002
There has to be a metanoia, which is a change of perception, a change in the whole way that we view life and the purpose of our lives.

148
00:18:43,663 --> 00:18:46,625
And of course, this is the role of religion.

149
00:18:47,567 --> 00:18:53,817
Science is very good at telling us how things come to be, but it can't answer the question why.

150
00:18:53,856 --> 00:19:06,336
All religions always posit something beyond this world that we're actually experiencing.

151
00:19:07,817 --> 00:19:13,086
If you turn just to the world and say, well, this is it and there's nothing else,

152
00:19:13,775 --> 00:19:18,040
then this becomes your aim, to make this world work for you.

153
00:19:18,922 --> 00:19:22,487
And it's very difficult not to make it a selfish enterprise.

154
00:19:23,568 --> 00:19:36,626
Of course, one begins to understand that if you turn outward, if you start doing things for other people as well as for yourself, then the payback is a deeper personal happiness.

155
00:19:37,248 --> 00:19:42,394
But that's not the way at the moment this neoliberalism is asking us to work.

156
00:19:42,454 --> 00:19:46,980
It's all about me getting as much as I can, dog eat dog and so forth.

157
00:19:48,163 --> 00:19:56,515
So what we need is as this wheel turning monarch is a change of values.

158
00:20:00,619 --> 00:20:06,208
So now I woke up today and I thought, I'm doing all the work here.

159
00:20:06,526 --> 00:20:11,471
